Italians sought to rediscover “spiritual values” in the Dolomites and the Alps that had been repressed by the smoke and grime of industry. Eugen Lammer’s classic Nietzschean hymn to the mountains, The Fountain of Youth (published in Italy in 1933), glorified rock-climbing without the use of maps and guides. Lammer’s book was known to Hitler and his Nazi cohorts. Mountain-worship was in keeping with Nazi-Teutonic pagan myths of the sublime and sub-Wagnerian kitsch in general.
